\subsection{Discussion: geometry}



	\subsubsection*{Moduli stacks}

	The proof of Theorem \ref{Th:eventual-hyperbolicity} follows  {\sc Mumford}'s ideas in \cite{Mumford}. To avoid convoluted allusions to ``orbifold structures", we systematically deploy the language of algebraic stacks.

	Denote by ${\widetilde{\mathcal{A}}}_g^{[m]}$ the moduli {\em stack} of principally polarized abelian varieties of dimension $g$ with full level-$m$ structure; see \cite[I.4.11, IV.6.2(c)]{Faltings-Chai}. Its coarse moduli space in the sense of  \cite{Keel-Mori} is ${\mathcal{A}}_g^{[m]}$; it is a fine moduli space provided $m \geq 3$, so ${\mathcal{A}}_g^{[m]} = {\widetilde{\mathcal{A}}}_g^{[m]}$ in this case. For $m=1$ we simply write ${\widetilde{\mathcal{A}}}_g:= {\widetilde{\mathcal{A}}}_g^{[1]}$.



	\subsubsection*{Logarithmic hyperbolicity}

	The proof of eventual hyperbolicity relies on the following:

	\begin{theorem}[Logarithmic hyperbolicity]\label{Th:log-hyp}
		Let $X \subset {\widetilde{\mathcal{A}}}_g$ be a closed substack, $X'\to X$ a resolution of singularities, $X' \subset \overline X'$ a smooth compactification with $D = \overline X' \smallsetminus X'  $ a normal crossings divisor.  Then $K_{\overline X'}+D$ is big.
	\end{theorem}

	Theorem \ref{Th:log-hyp} says that, after some technical choices of resolutions and compactifications, a substack of the moduli stack ${\widetilde{\mathcal{A}}}_g$ is of logarithmic general type: its canonical divisor class might not be big, but adding the normal crossings boundary divisor returns a big class.

	The engine behind logarithmic hyperbolicity is a recent general result \cite[Theorem A]{Popa-Schnell} of {\sc Popa} and {\sc Schnell}, which in turn uses {Viehweg-Zuo} sheaves and mixed Hodge modules (both {\sc Campana} and {\sc Popa} expect that the methods of {\sc Viehweg-Zuo} \cite{Viehweg-Zuo-base}, combined with results of {\sc Campana-Paun} \cite{Campana-Paun}, which do not use mixed Hodge modules, should also apply in our case). We apply this result directly to subschemes of ${\widetilde{\mathcal{A}}}_g^{[m]}$ with any $m\geq 3$ in Proposition \ref{Prop:hyp-m}, and we use a descent argument to prove Theorem \ref{Th:log-hyp}.

	Big divisors can be perturbed slightly and remain big, yielding:

	\begin{corollary}\label{Cor:epsilon}
		There is an $\epsilon>0$ such that  $K_{\overline X'}+ (1-\epsilon)D$ is big.
	\end{corollary}


An immediate sample  result in the spirit of Corollary \ref{cor:Mg} is the following:

	\begin{corollary}
		\label{cor:KMg}
		Let $\Delta_0\subset {\overline{\mathcal{M}}}_g$ be the boundary divisor of irreducible nodal curves on the Deligne--Mumford stack of stable curves. Then $K_{{\overline{\mathcal{M}}}_g}+\Delta_0$ is big. 
	\end{corollary}

{\sc Gavril Farkas} also pointed out that Corollary~\ref{cor:KMg} is also an easy consequence of the well-known relationships between divisors on ${\overline{\mathcal{M}}}_g$: the divisor $K_{{\overline{\mathcal{M}}}_g}+\Delta_0$ can be easily written as a positive combination of the hodge class $\lambda$, which is big and nef, and the boundary divisors $\Delta_i$ and the Brill-Noether divisor $BN_g$, which are effective.


	\subsubsection*{Toroidal compactifications}

	To get from logarithmic hyperbolicity in the form of~Corollary~\ref{Cor:epsilon} to eventual hyperbolicity, we must bridge the gap between the perturbed logarithmic canonical class $K + D-\epsilon D$ and an actual canonical class $K + D - D = K$. {\sc Mumford}'s idea in \cite[Proposition~4.4]{Mumford} is that, by adding level structure to the ambient stack ${\widetilde{\mathcal{A}}}_g$, we can force enough ramification over $D$ in the moduli stack with level structure to turn straw ($-\epsilon D$) into gold ($-D$). 

