\subsection{Proof of Corollary~\ref{Th:strong-eventual-hyperbolicity}}

	First, apply Theorem~\ref{Th:eventual-hyperbolicity} to $X = {\mathcal{A}}_g$, to see there is an integer $r_g$ such that, for each $r \geq r_g$, every component of ${\mathcal{A}}_g^{[p^r]}$ is of general type. By {\sc Lang}'s geometric conjecture~\ref{conj:geomLang}, there is a proper closed subscheme $\Xi_r \subset {\mathcal{A}}_g^{[p^r]}$ that contains all the positive-dimensional subvarieties of ${\mathcal{A}}_g^{[p^r]}$ that are not of general type. For each $i > r_g$, let $W_i = \pi_{p^i}(\Xi_i)$. The $W_i$ form a descending chain of closed subsets of ${\mathcal{A}}_g$: indeed, the morphism $\pi_{p^i}$ factors through $\pi_{p^j}$ for $i > j$, and the map ${\mathcal{A}}_g^{p^i} \to {\mathcal{A}}_g^{p^j}$ is dominant, so the image of a subvariety not of general type must be a subvariety that is also not of general type. This chain must stabilize because ${\mathcal{A}}_g$ is a Noetherian topological space. Say $W_n = W_{n + 1} = \cdots$.

	We claim, as in the proof of Theorem~\ref{Th:main}, that $\dim W_n \leq 0$. Suppose otherwise, and let $X \subseteq W_n$ be an irreducible component of positive dimension. By eventual hyperbolicity (Theorem~\ref{Th:eventual-hyperbolicity}), every irreducible component of $\pi_{p^m}^{-1}(X)$ is of general type, for all $m \gg n$. By {\sc Lang}'s geometric conjecture~\ref{conj:geomLang}, there is a proper closed subscheme $Y_m$ of $\pi_{p^m}^{-1}(X)$ that contains all the subvarieties of $\pi_{p^m}^{-1}(X)$ that are not of general type. But then $\pi_{p^m}(Y_m)$ is a proper closed subscheme of $X$ contained in $W_m = W_n$.  Hence $X$ is not an irreducible component of $W_n$ after all, contradicting its definition.

	Since $\pi_{p^n}$ is finite, we must have $\dim \Xi_n \leq 0$, and thus every subvariety of ${\mathcal{A}}_g^{[p^n]}$ is of general type.\qed





\subsection{Proof of Corollary~\ref{Th:uniform-strong}} 

	By Corollary~\ref{Th:strong-eventual-hyperbolicity}, there is an integer $r$ such that every subvariety of $X_r := {\mathcal{A}}_g^{[p^r]}$ is of general type. By {\sc Lang}'s strong conjecture~\ref{conj:StrongLang}, which follows from our hypotheses, there is a proper closed subscheme $\Xi_r \subset X_r$ such that $X_r(K)\setminus \Xi_r(K)$ is finite for every number field $K$. But (every irreducible component of) $\Xi_r$ is itself of general type, and its dimension is smaller than that of $X_r$'s, so we may apply {\sc Lang}'s strong conjecture to (the components of) $\Xi_r$ and conclude there is a proper closed subscheme $\Xi'_r \subset \Xi_r$ such that $\Xi_r(K) \setminus \Xi'_r(K)$ is finite for every number field $K$. Continuing inductively, we conclude that $X_r(K)$ is finite for every number field $K$; the integer $r$ does not depend on $K$.\qed



